00:23:59.520 --> 00:24:06.479
You also pick an embedding function at the time that you create a store so here we're using an embedding model from open AI

00:24:07.359 --> 00:24:09.359
embedding models are

00:24:09.839 --> 00:24:13.280
basically functions that transform a piece of string or a

00:24:13.959 --> 00:24:20.199
piece of text into a numeric vector and the magic of them is that similar meaning strings

00:24:20.520 --> 00:24:23.880
Transform to similar vectors and this magic comes from machine learning

00:24:23.880 --> 00:24:28.640
So embedding models are typically large things kind of like LLMs and you'll access them through a provider

00:24:30.800 --> 00:24:35.680
In Ragnar we're using embeddings to do semantic search or that's what powers the search

00:24:35.959 --> 00:24:38.239
But you can use embeddings for lots of other things, too

00:24:39.160 --> 00:24:43.680
There are built-in functions for lots of major embedding providers

00:24:44.079 --> 00:24:49.199
But I also want to point out you can provide your own embedding function. You're not gated by us implementing something

00:24:49.800 --> 00:24:54.199
Once you've created your store, the next step is figure out what you want in that store

00:24:54.199 --> 00:24:56.599
If you have a bunch of local files, you can just list them

00:24:56.599 --> 00:25:01.839
If you want to scrape a website, you can use Ragnar find links and you'll get a nice character vector of URLs

00:25:02.520 --> 00:25:06.640
This function has a lot of bells and whistles. It'll like validate links and stuff

00:25:07.880 --> 00:25:10.520
And then once you have a list of all your documents

00:25:10.520 --> 00:25:14.000
You're going to iterate through them one at a time and then for each one

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:16.160
The first thing you're going to do is you're going to call read as markdown

00:25:16.199 --> 00:25:19.479
So read as markdown is a very wide funnel

00:25:19.479 --> 00:25:23.719
You can throw almost anything at it and you can get back something that looks like markdown

00:25:23.719 --> 00:25:26.199
And markdown is a great format for LLMs in general

00:25:28.719 --> 00:25:34.040
Once you have your piece of markdown text, you want to split it into smaller chunks or excerpts

00:25:34.040 --> 00:25:38.839
And for this function, for this task, Ragnar provides markdown chunk

00:25:38.839 --> 00:25:44.479
And markdown chunks are basically just a bunch of text that you're going to put in a single file

00:25:45.319 --> 00:25:48.439
And markdown chunk is quite a fancy function

00:25:48.439 --> 00:25:53.880
I would describe it in a phrase as semantic boundary aware strided chunking

00:25:53.880 --> 00:26:01.280
It tries to pick smart boundary positions so it doesn't cut off in the middle of a word, for example

00:26:01.280 --> 00:26:08.880
Markdown chunk returns a data frame of start and end positions as integers

00:26:08.880 --> 00:26:11.760
It returns the text and then it has one other trick that it does

00:26:11.760 --> 00:26:17.560
It generates a context column so for every chunk it also assembles all the markdown headings

00:26:17.560 --> 00:26:19.959
That are in scope for that chunk position

00:26:19.959 --> 00:26:23.359
That really helps situate that excerpt for the LLM

00:26:26.359 --> 00:26:29.160
Once you have your chunks, you insert them into the store

00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:32.160
And then once you've done that for all your documents, you build your index

00:26:32.160 --> 00:26:36.560
And now you're ready to search or hook up an LLM to do search

