You can also submit things like images or pdfs with your chat

00:36:43.159 --> 00:36:47.159
Input, so the main thing here is you're going to want to use

00:36:47.159 --> 00:36:50.159
One of the content helpers.

00:36:50.159 --> 00:36:53.159
You can attach images from urls or local files.

00:36:53.159 --> 00:36:56.159
You can also attach pdf files.

00:36:56.159 --> 00:37:00.159
That won't work with, like, every model, but at least for

00:37:00.159 --> 00:37:04.159
Models that support these kind of non-text inputs, you're able

00:37:04.159 --> 00:37:08.159
To use these content helpers.

00:37:08.159 --> 00:37:12.159
And here it's able to recognize, oh, this is actually an image

00:37:12.159 --> 00:37:14.159
Of bender.

00:37:14.159 --> 00:37:16.159
So that's great.

00:37:16.159 --> 00:37:19.159
But an example of an llm limitation.

00:37:19.159 --> 00:37:23.159
Again, this was kind of part of some of hadley's points in the

00:37:23.159 --> 00:37:27.159
Keynote, where llms have this important limitation of kind of

00:37:27.159 --> 00:37:31.159
A fixed cutoff date in terms of their knowledge set.

00:37:31.159 --> 00:37:35.159
So brag is kind of one way to address this limitation in a

00:37:35.159 --> 00:37:39.159
Sense.

00:37:39.159 --> 00:37:43.159
Where, well, first, if i first ask this question, it's going to

00:37:43.159 --> 00:37:47.159
Say, basically, i don't know what the current weather is in

00:37:47.159 --> 00:37:49.159
Atlanta, georgia.

00:37:49.159 --> 00:37:52.159
So rag would be some way of kind of providing additional

00:37:52.159 --> 00:37:55.159
Context to a model to answer questions that they don't have

00:37:55.159 --> 00:37:57.159
The knowledge for.

00:37:57.159 --> 00:38:00.159
Another way of addressing this problem is supplying tools to

00:38:00.159 --> 00:38:02.159
The llm.

00:38:02.159 --> 00:38:06.159
And in this case, meaning, like, python functions.

00:38:06.159 --> 00:38:10.159
And providing tools in chat list is quite easy.

00:38:11.159 --> 00:38:15.159
Kind of the base requirements here is you're going to want to

00:38:15.159 --> 00:38:19.159
Probably use type annotations on the input parameters so that

00:38:19.159 --> 00:38:25.159
The model knows, like, what kind of input i'm allowed to

00:38:25.159 --> 00:38:28.159
Provide as input values to this tool.

00:38:28.159 --> 00:38:33.159
As well as a doc string to just generally kind of tell the

00:38:33.159 --> 00:38:37.159
Model, both the model and yourself, like, what is this

00:38:38.159 --> 00:38:40.159
Function useful for.

00:38:40.159 --> 00:38:43.159
And also provides a kind of natural place to document

00:38:43.159 --> 00:38:45.159
Parameters.

00:38:45.159 --> 00:38:49.159
So i'm going to just take this function and register it with

00:38:49.159 --> 00:38:51.159
My chat session.

00:38:51.159 --> 00:38:54.159
And then ask the same question again.

00:38:54.159 --> 00:39:00.159
And now we'll see in the output here some nice output

00:39:00.159 --> 00:39:03.159
Suggesting that the llm has made a tool request.

00:39:03.159 --> 00:39:06.159
And it's actually kind of inferred a latitude and

00:39:06.159 --> 00:39:08.159
Distance for me based on the city location.

00:39:08.159 --> 00:39:12.159
That's just kind of some of the magic of the llm.

00:39:12.159 --> 00:39:14.159
But it's making the request.

00:39:14.159 --> 00:39:18.159
And then the python session and chat list is handling the actual

00:39:18.159 --> 00:39:21.159
Execution of that tool based on the request.

00:39:21.159 --> 00:39:25.159
Getting the tool result, passing that back to the llm.

00:39:25.159 --> 00:39:28.159
And then it takes that information and generates a

00:39:28.159 --> 00:39:33.159
Response for me based on that tool result.

00:39:33.159 --> 00:39:36.159
Another big feature is the ability to force the model to

00:39:36.159 --> 00:39:38.159
Give you structured output.

00:39:38.159 --> 00:39:41.159
Again, we saw an example of this in the keynote.

00:39:41.159 --> 00:39:45.159
But the python way of doing this is to use the package.

